# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cool-flame
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cool-flame/acids] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:cool-flame/acids] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:cool-flame/acids] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:cool-flame/acids] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:cool-flame/acids] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:cool-flame/acids] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:cool-flame/acids] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:cool-flame/acids] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:cool-flame/acids] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:cool-flame/acids] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:cool-flame/acids] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:cool-flame/acids] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:cool-flame/acids] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:cool-flame/acids] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:cool-flame/acids] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:cool-flame/acids] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:cool-flame/acids] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:cool-flame/acids] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:cool-flame/acids] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:cool-flame/acids] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:cool-flame/acids] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:cool-flame/acids] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:cool-flame/acids] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:cool-flame/acids] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:cool-flame/acids] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:cool-flame/acids] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:cool-flame/acids] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:cool-flame/acids] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:cool-flame/acids] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:cool-flame/acids] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:cool-flame/acids] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:cool-flame/acids] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:cool-flame/acids] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:cool-flame/acids] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:cool-flame/acids] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In organic chemistry, an **aldehyde** (/ˈældɪhaɪd/) (lat.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] *al*cohol *dehyd*rogenatum, dehydrogenated alcohol) is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure R−CH=O.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The functional group itself (without the "R" side chain) can be referred to as an **aldehyde** but can also be classified as a **formyl group**.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes are a common motif in many chemicals important in technology and biology.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehyde molecules have a central carbon atom that is connected by a double bond to oxygen, a single bond to hydrogen and another single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The C=O bond length is about 120–122 picometers.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes have properties that are diverse and that depend on the remainder of the molecule.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Smaller aldehydes such as formaldehyde and acetaldehyde are soluble in water, and the volatile aldehydes have pungent odors.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes can be identified by spectroscopic methods.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Using IR spectroscopy, they display a strong *ν*CO band near 1700 cm−1.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In their 1H NMR spectra, the formyl hydrogen center absorbs near *δ*H 9.5 to 10, which is a distinctive part of the spectrum.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This signal shows the characteristic coupling to any protons on the α carbon with a small coupling constant typically less than 3.0 Hz.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The 13C NMR spectra of aldehydes and ketones gives a suppressed (weak) but distinctive signal at *δ*C 190 to 205.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Important aldehydes and related compounds.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Traces of many aldehydes are found in essential oils and often contribute to their pleasant odours, including cinnamaldehyde, cilantro, and vanillin.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Possibly due to the high reactivity of the formyl group, aldehydes are not commonly found in organic "building block" molecules, such as amino acids, nucleic acids, and lipids.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] However, most sugars are derivatives of aldehydes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] These aldoses exist as hemiacetals, a sort of masked form of the parent aldehyde.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] For example, in aqueous solution only a tiny fraction of glucose exists as the aldehyde.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Of the several methods for preparing aldehydes, one dominant technology is hydroformylation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Hydroformylation is conducted on a very large scale for diverse aldehydes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] It involves treatment of the alkene with a mixture of hydrogen gas and carbon monoxide in the presence of a metal catalyst.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The largest operations involve methanol and ethanol respectively to formaldehyde and acetaldehyde, which are produced on multimillion ton scale annually.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Other large scale aldehydes are produced by autoxidation of hydrocarbons: benzaldehyde from toluene, acrolein from propylene, and methacrolein from isobutene.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the Wacker process, oxidation of ethylene to acetaldehyde in the presence of copper and palladium catalysts, is also used.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] "Green" and cheap oxygen (or air) is the oxidant of choice.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Laboratories may instead apply a wide variety of specialized oxidizing agents, which are often consumed stoichiometrically.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Oxidation can be achieved by heating the alcohol with an acidified solution of potassium dichromate.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In this case, excess dichromate will further oxidize the aldehyde to a carboxylic acid, so either the aldehyde is distilled out as it forms (if volatile) or milder reagents such as PCC are used.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] A variety of reagent systems achieve aldehydes under chromium-free conditions.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] One such are the hypervalent organoiodine compounds (i.e., IBX acid, Dess–Martin periodinane), although these often also oxidize the α position.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] A Lux-Flood acid will activate various sulfoxides (e.g. the Swern oxidation), and amine oxides convert alkyl halides to aldehydes (e.g., the Ganem oxidation).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Sterically-hindered nitroxyls (i.e., TEMPO) can catalyze aldehyde formation with a cheaper oxidant.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Alternatively, vicinal diols or their oxidized sequelae (acyloins or α-hydroxy acids) can be oxidized with cleavage to two aldehydes or an aldehyde and carbon dioxide.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes participate in many reactions.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] From the biological perspective, the key reactions involve addition of nucleophiles to the formyl carbon in the formation of imines (oxidative deamination) and hemiacetals (structures of aldose sugars).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Because of resonance stabilization of the conjugate base, an α-hydrogen in an aldehyde is weakly acidic with a p*K*a near 17.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The formyl proton itself does not readily undergo deprotonation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes (except those without an alpha carbon, or without protons on the alpha carbon, such as formaldehyde and benzaldehyde) can exist in either the keto or the enol tautomer.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Keto–enol tautomerism is catalyzed by either acid or base.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In neutral solution, the enol is the minority tautomer, reversing several times per second.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] But it becomes the dominant tautomer in strong acid or base solutions, and enolized aldehydes undergo nucleophilic attack at the α position.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The formyl group can be readily reduced to a primary alcohol (−CH2OH).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Typically this conversion is accomplished by catalytic hydrogenation either directly or by transfer hydrogenation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Stoichiometric reductions are also popular, as can be effected with sodium borohydride.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The formyl group readily oxidizes to the corresponding carboxyl group (−COOH).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The preferred oxidant in industry is oxygen or air.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the laboratory, popular oxidizing agents include potassium permanganate, nitric acid, chromium(VI) oxide, and chromic acid.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The combination of manganese dioxide, cyanide, acetic acid and methanol will convert the aldehyde to a methyl ester.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Another oxidation reaction is the basis of the *silver-mirror test*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This reagent converts aldehydes to carboxylic acids without attacking carbon–carbon double bonds.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The name *silver-mirror test* arises because this reaction produces a precipitate of silver, whose presence can be used to test for the presence of an aldehyde.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] A further oxidation reaction involves Fehling's reagent as a test.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The Cu2+ complex ions are reduced to a red-brick-coloured Cu2O precipitate.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aromatic aldehydes, such as benzaldehyde, do not give a positive Fehling's test, because they are not easily oxidized by mild oxidizing agents like Fehling's reagent.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The benzene ring provides stability, while steric hindrance prevents the formation of the required hydrated anion intermediate.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] If the aldehyde cannot form an enolate (e.g., benzaldehyde), addition of strong base induces the Cannizzaro reaction.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This reaction results in disproportionation, producing a mixture of alcohol and carboxylic acid.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Nucleophiles add readily to the carbonyl group.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In many cases, a water molecule is removed after the addition takes place; in this case, the reaction is classed as an addition–elimination or addition–condensation reaction.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] There are many variations of nucleophilic addition reactions.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the acetalisation reaction, under acidic or basic conditions, an alcohol adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred to form a hemiacetal.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Under acidic conditions, the hemiacetal and the alcohol can further react to form an acetal and water.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Simple hemiacetals are usually unstable, although cyclic ones such as glucose can be stable.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Acetals are stable, but revert to the aldehyde in the presence of acid.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Aldehydes can react with water to form hydrates, R−CH(OH)2.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] These diols are stable when strong electron withdrawing groups are present, as in chloral hydrate.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The mechanism of formation is identical to hemiacetal formation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Another aldehyde molecule can also act as the nucleophile to give polymeric or oligomeric acetals called paraldehydes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In alkylimino-de-oxo-bisubstitution, a primary or secondary amine adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred from the nitrogen to the oxygen atom to create a carbinolamine.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the case of a primary amine, a water molecule can be eliminated from the carbinolamine intermediate to yield an imine or its trimer, a hexahydrotriazine This reaction is catalyzed by acid.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) can also add to the carbonyl group.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] After the elimination of water, this results in an oxime.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] An ammonia derivative of the form H2NNR2 such as hydrazine (H2NNH2) or 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine can also be the nucleophile and after the elimination of water, resulting in the formation of a hydrazone, which are usually orange crystalline solids.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This reaction forms the basis of a test for aldehydes and ketones.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The cyano group in HCN can add to the carbonyl group to form cyanohydrins, R−CH(OH)CN.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In this reaction the CN− ion is the nucleophile that attacks the partially positive carbon atom of the carbonyl group.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The mechanism involves a pair of electrons from the carbonyl-group double bond transferring to the oxygen atom, leaving it single-bonded to carbon and giving the oxygen atom a negative charge.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This intermediate ion rapidly reacts with H+, such as from the HCN molecule, to form the alcohol group of the cyanohydrin.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Organometallic compounds, such as organolithium reagents, Grignard reagents, or acetylides, undergo nucleophilic addition reactions, yielding a substituted alcohol group.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Related reactions include organostannane additions, Barbier reactions, and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the aldol reaction, the metal enolates of ketones, esters, amides, and carboxylic acids add to aldehydes to form β-hydroxycarbonyl compounds (aldols).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Acid or base-catalyzed dehydration then leads to α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The combination of these two steps is known as the aldol condensation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The Prins reaction occurs when a nucleophilic alkene or alkyne reacts with an aldehyde as electrophile.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The product of the Prins reaction varies with reaction conditions and substrates employed.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This reaction is used as a test for aldehydes and is useful for separation or purification of aldehydes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] A **dialdehyde** is an organic chemical compound with two aldehyde groups.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The nomenclature of dialdehydes have the ending *-dial* or sometimes *-dialdehyde*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Short aliphatic dialdehydes are sometimes named after the diacid from which they can be derived.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] An example is butanedial, which is also called succinaldehyde (from succinic acid).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Some aldehydes are substrates for aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes which metabolize aldehydes in the body.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] There are toxicities associated with some aldehydes that are related to neurodegenerative disease, heart disease, and some types of cancer.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Of all aldehydes, formaldehyde is produced on the largest scale, about 6000000 tons per year.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] It is mainly used in the production of resins when combined with urea, melamine, and phenol (e.g., Bakelite).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] It is a precursor to methylene diphenyl diisocyanate ("MDI"), a precursor to polyurethanes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The second main aldehyde is butyraldehyde, of which about 2500000 tons per year are prepared by hydroformylation.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] It is the principal precursor to 2-ethylhexanol, which is used as a plasticizer.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Acetaldehyde once was a dominating product, but production levels have declined to less than 1000000 tons per year because it mainly served as a precursor to acetic acid, which is now prepared by carbonylation of methanol.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Many other aldehydes find commercial applications, often as precursors to alcohols, the so-called oxo alcohols, which are used in detergents.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Some aldehydes are produced only on a small scale (less than 1000 tons per year) and are used as ingredients in flavours and perfumes such as Chanel No.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Fresh, green, citrusy and nutty notes in perfumes are often due to aldehydes.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] These include cinnamaldehyde and its derivatives, citral, and lilial.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The common names for aldehydes do not strictly follow official guidelines, such as those recommended by IUPAC, but these rules are useful.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In other cases, such as when a −CHO group is attached to a ring, the suffix *-carbaldehyde* may be used.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] Thus, C6H11CHO is known as *cyclohexanecarbaldehyde*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] If the presence of another functional group demands the use of a suffix, the aldehyde group is named with the prefix *formyl-*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This prefix is preferred to *methanoyl-*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] If the compound is a natural product or a carboxylic acid, the prefix *oxo-* may be used to indicate which carbon atom is part of the aldehyde group; for example, CHOCH2COOH is named *2-oxoethanoic acid*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] If replacing the aldehyde group with a carboxyl group (−COOH) would yield a carboxylic acid with a trivial name, the aldehyde may be named by replacing the suffix *-ic acid* or *-oic acid* in this trivial name by *-aldehyde*.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The word *aldehyde* was coined by Justus von Liebig as a contraction of the Latin ***al**cohol **dehyd**rogenatus* (dehydrogenated alcohol).
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] In the past, aldehydes were sometimes named after the corresponding alcohols, for example, *vinous aldehyde* for acetaldehyde.
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] The term *formyl group* is derived from the Latin word *formica* "ant".
[src:cool-flame/aldehydes] This word can be recognized in the simplest aldehyde, formaldehyde, and in the simplest carboxylic acid, formic acid.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] This temperature is required to supply the activation energy needed for combustion.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] The temperature at which a chemical ignites decreases as the pressure is decreased.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] Substances which spontaneously ignite in a normal atmosphere at naturally ambient temperatures are termed pyrophoric.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] Autoignition temperatures of liquid chemicals are typically measured using a 500-millilitre (18 imp fl oz; 17 US fl oz) flask placed in a temperature-controlled oven in accordance with the procedure described in ASTM E659.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] When measured for plastics, autoignition temperature can also be measured under elevated pressure and at 100% oxygen concentration.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] The resulting value is used as a predictor of viability for high-oxygen service.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] The main testing standard for this is ASTM G72.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] where *k* = thermal conductivity, *ρ* = density, and *c* = specific heat capacity of the material of interest, $T_{0}$ is the initial temperature of the material (or the temperature of the bulk material).
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] Temperatures vary widely in the literature and should only be used as estimates.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] Factors that may cause variation include partial pressure of oxygen, altitude, humidity, and amount of time required for ignition.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] Generally the autoignition temperature for hydrocarbon/air mixtures decreases with increasing molecular mass and increasing chain length.
[src:cool-flame/auto-ignition-temperature] The autoignition temperature is also higher for branched-chain hydrocarbons than for straight-chain hydrocarbons.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In physics and fluid mechanics, a **boundary layer** is the thin layer of fluid in the immediate vicinity of a bounding surface formed by the fluid flowing along the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The fluid's interaction with the wall induces a no-slip boundary condition (zero velocity at the wall).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The flow velocity then monotonically increases above the surface until it returns to the bulk flow velocity.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The thin layer consisting of fluid whose velocity has not yet returned to the bulk flow velocity is called the velocity boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The air next to a human is heated, resulting in gravity-induced convective airflow, which results in both a velocity and thermal boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] A breeze disrupts the boundary layer, and hair and clothing protect it, making the human feel cooler or warmer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] On an aircraft wing, the velocity boundary layer is the part of the flow close to the wing, where viscous forces distort the surrounding non-viscous flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In the Earth's atmosphere, the atmospheric boundary layer is the air layer (~ 1 km) near the ground.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It is affected by the surface; day-night heat flows caused by the sun heating the ground, moisture, or momentum transfer to or from the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Laminar boundary layers can be loosely classified according to their structure and the circumstances under which they are created.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] When a fluid rotates and viscous forces are balanced by the Coriolis effect (rather than convective inertia), an Ekman layer forms.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In the theory of heat transfer, a thermal boundary layer occurs.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] A surface can have multiple types of boundary layer simultaneously.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The viscous nature of airflow reduces the local velocities on a surface and is responsible for skin friction.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The layer of air over the wing's surface that is slowed down or stopped by viscosity, is the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] There are two different types of boundary layer flow: laminar and turbulent.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The laminar boundary is a very smooth flow, while the turbulent boundary layer contains swirls or "eddies." The laminar flow creates less skin friction drag than the turbulent flow, but is less stable.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Boundary layer flow over a wing surface begins as a smooth laminar flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] As the flow continues back from the leading edge, the laminar boundary layer increases in thickness.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] At some distance back from the leading edge, the smooth laminar flow breaks down and transitions to a turbulent flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] From a drag standpoint, it is advisable to have the transition from laminar to turbulent flow as far aft on the wing as possible, or have a large amount of the wing surface within the laminar portion of the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The low energy laminar flow, however, tends to break down more suddenly than the turbulent layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The aerodynamic boundary layer was first hypothesized by Ludwig Prandtl in a paper presented on August 12, 1904, at the third International Congress of Mathematicians in Heidelberg, Germany.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This allows a closed-form solution for the flow in both areas by making significant simplifications of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The same hypothesis is applicable to other fluids (besides air) with moderate to low viscosity such as water.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For the case where there is a temperature difference between the surface and the bulk fluid, it is found that the majority of the heat transfer to and from a body takes place in the vicinity of the velocity boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This again allows the equations to be simplified in the flow field outside the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The pressure distribution throughout the boundary layer in the direction normal to the surface (such as an airfoil) remains relatively constant throughout the boundary layer, and is the same as on the surface itself.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The thickness of the velocity boundary layer is normally defined as the distance from the solid body to the point at which the viscous flow velocity is 99% of the freestream velocity (the surface velocity of an inviscid flow).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Displacement thickness is an alternative definition stating that the boundary layer represents a deficit in mass flow compared to inviscid flow with slip at the wall.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It is the distance by which the wall would have to be displaced in the inviscid case to give the same total mass flow as the viscous case.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The no-slip condition requires the flow velocity at the surface of a solid object be zero and the fluid temperature be equal to the temperature of the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The flow velocity will then increase rapidly within the boundary layer, governed by the boundary layer equations, below.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The thermal boundary layer thickness is similarly the distance from the body at which the temperature is 99% of the freestream temperature.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The ratio of the two thicknesses is governed by the Prandtl number.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is 1, the two boundary layers are the same thickness.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is greater than 1, the thermal boundary layer is thinner than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is less than 1, which is the case for air at standard conditions, the thermal boundary layer is thicker than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In high-performance designs, such as gliders and commercial aircraft, much attention is paid to controlling the behavior of the boundary layer to minimize drag.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] First, the boundary layer adds to the effective thickness of the body, through the displacement thickness, hence increasing the pressure drag.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Secondly, the shear forces at the surface of the wing create skin friction drag.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] At high Reynolds numbers, typical of full-sized aircraft, it is desirable to have a laminar boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This results in a lower skin friction due to the characteristic velocity profile of laminar flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] However, the boundary layer inevitably thickens and becomes less stable as the flow develops along the body, and eventually becomes turbulent, the process known as boundary layer transition.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] One way of dealing with this problem is to suck the boundary layer away through a porous surface (see Boundary layer suction).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This can reduce drag, but is usually impractical due to its mechanical complexity and the power required to move the air and dispose of it.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Natural laminar flow (NLF) techniques push the boundary layer transition aft by reshaping the airfoil or fuselage so that its thickest point is more aft and less thick.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This reduces the velocities in the leading part and the same Reynolds number is achieved with a greater length.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] At lower Reynolds numbers, such as those seen with model aircraft, it is relatively easy to maintain laminar flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This gives low skin friction, which is desirable.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] However, the same velocity profile which gives the laminar boundary layer its low skin friction also causes it to be badly affected by adverse pressure gradients.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] As the pressure begins to recover over the rear part of the wing chord, a laminar boundary layer will tend to separate from the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Such flow separation causes a large increase in the pressure drag, since it greatly increases the effective size of the wing section.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In these cases, it can be advantageous to deliberately trip the boundary layer into turbulence at a point prior to the location of laminar separation, using a turbulator.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The fuller velocity profile of the turbulent boundary layer allows it to sustain the adverse pressure gradient without separating.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Thus, although the skin friction is increased, overall drag is decreased.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This is the principle behind the dimpling on golf balls, as well as vortex generators on aircraft.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Special wing sections have also been designed which tailor the pressure recovery so laminar separation is reduced or even eliminated.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This represents an optimum compromise between the pressure drag from flow separation and skin friction from induced turbulence.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] When using half-models in wind tunnels, a peniche is sometimes used to reduce or eliminate the effect of the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The deduction of the **boundary layer equations** was one of the most important advances in fluid dynamics.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Using an order of magnitude analysis, the well-known governing Navier–Stokes equations of viscous fluid flow can be greatly simplified within the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Notably, the characteristic of the partial differential equations (PDE) becomes parabolic, rather than the elliptical form of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This greatly simplifies the solution of the equations.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] By making the boundary layer approximation, the flow is divided into an inviscid portion (which is easy to solve by a number of methods) and the boundary layer, which is governed by an easier to solve PDE.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] where u and $\upsilon$ are the velocity components, $\rho$ is the density, p is the pressure, and $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid at a point.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The approximation states that, for a sufficiently high Reynolds number the flow over a surface can be divided into an outer region of inviscid flow unaffected by viscosity (the majority of the flow), and a region close to the surface where viscosity is important (the boundary layer).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Let u and $\upsilon$ be streamwise and transverse (wall normal) velocities respectively inside the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The order of magnitude analysis assumes the streamwise length scale significantly larger than the transverse length scale inside the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It follows that variations in properties in the streamwise direction are generally much lower than those in the wall normal direction.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Apply this to the continuity equation shows that $\upsilon$ , the wall normal velocity, is small compared with u the streamwise velocity.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Since the static pressure p is independent of y , then pressure at the edge of the boundary layer is the pressure throughout the boundary layer at a given streamwise position.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The external pressure may be obtained through an application of Bernoulli's equation.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Let U be the fluid velocity outside the boundary layer, where u and U are both parallel.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] These approximations are used in a variety of practical flow problems of scientific and engineering interest.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The above analysis is for any instantaneous laminar or turbulent boundary layer, but is used mainly in laminar flow studies since the mean flow is also the instantaneous flow because there are no velocity fluctuations present.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This simplified equation is a parabolic PDE and can be solved using a similarity solution often referred to as the Blasius boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Since the solution is not unique from mathematical perspective, to the solution can be added any one of an infinite set of eigenfunctions as shown by Stewartson and Paul A.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Von Kármán derived the integral equation by integrating the boundary layer equation across the boundary layer in 1921.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The energy integral was derived by Wieghardt.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional boundary layers, von Mises introduced a transformation which takes x and $\psi$ (stream function) as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\chi =U^{2}-u^{2}$ instead of u .
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This transformation is later extended to compressible boundary layer by von Kármán and HS Tsien.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional compressible boundary layer, Luigi Crocco introduced a transformation which takes x and u as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\tau =\mu \partial u/\partial y$ (shear stress) instead of u .
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The treatment of turbulent boundary layers is far more difficult due to the time-dependent variation of the flow properties.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] One of the most widely used techniques in which turbulent flows are tackled is to apply Reynolds decomposition.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Here the instantaneous flow properties are decomposed into a mean and fluctuating component with the assumption that the mean of the fluctuating component is always zero.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Using a similar order-of-magnitude analysis, the above equations can be reduced to leading order terms.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This equation does not satisfy the no-slip condition at the wall.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Like Prandtl did for his boundary layer equations, a new, smaller length scale must be used to allow the viscous term to become leading order in the momentum equation.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In the limit of infinite Reynolds number, the pressure gradient term can be shown to have no effect on the inner region of the turbulent boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The new "inner length scale" $\eta$ is a viscous length scale, and is of order ${\frac {\nu }{u_{*}}}$ , with $u_{*}$ being the velocity scale of the turbulent fluctuations, in this case a friction velocity.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Unlike the laminar boundary layer equations, the presence of two regimes governed by different sets of flow scales (i.e. the inner and outer scaling) has made finding a universal similarity solution for the turbulent boundary layer difficult and controversial.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] To find a similarity solution that spans both regions of the flow, it is necessary to asymptotically match the solutions from both regions of the flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Such analysis will yield either the so-called log-law or power-law.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Similar approaches to the above analysis has also been applied for thermal boundary layers, using the energy equation in compressible flows.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The additional term ${\overline {u'v'}}$ in the turbulent boundary layer equations is known as the Reynolds shear stress and is unknown a priori.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The solution of the turbulent boundary layer equations therefore necessitates the use of a turbulence model, which aims to express the Reynolds shear stress in terms of known flow variables or derivatives.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The lack of accuracy and generality of such models is a major obstacle in the successful prediction of turbulent flow properties in modern fluid dynamics.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] A constant stress layer exists in the near wall region.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Due to the damping of the vertical velocity fluctuations near the wall, the Reynolds stress term will become negligible and we find that a linear velocity profile exists.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This is only true for the very near wall region.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In 1928, the French engineer André Lévêque observed that convective heat transfer in a flowing fluid is affected only by the velocity values very close to the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For flows of large Prandtl number, the temperature/mass transition from surface to freestream temperature takes place across a very thin region close to the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Therefore, the most important fluid velocities are those inside this very thin region in which the change in velocity can be considered linear with normal distance from the surface.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] where *θ* is the tangent of the Poiseuille parabola intersecting the wall.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Although Lévêque's solution was specific to heat transfer into a Poiseuille flow, his insight helped lead other scientists to an exact solution of the thermal boundary-layer problem.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Schuh observed that in a boundary-layer, *u* is again a linear function of *y*, but that in this case, the wall tangent is a function of *x*.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This results in a very good approximation, even for low $Pr$ numbers, so that only liquid metals with $Pr$ much less than 1 cannot be treated this way.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In 1962, Kestin and Persen published a paper describing solutions for heat transfer when the thermal boundary layer is contained entirely within the momentum layer and for various wall temperature distributions.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For the problem of a flat plate with a temperature jump at $x=x_{0}$ , they propose a substitution that reduces the parabolic thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The solution to this equation, the temperature at any point in the fluid, can be expressed as an incomplete gamma function.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Schlichting proposed an equivalent substitution that reduces the thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation whose solution is the same incomplete gamma function.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Analytic solutions can be derived with the time-dependent self-similar Ansatz for the incompressible boundary layer equations including heat conduction.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] As is well known from several textbooks, heat transfer tends to decrease with the increase in the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Recently, it was observed on a practical and large scale that wind flowing through a photovoltaic generator tends to "trap" heat in the PV panels under a turbulent regime due to the decrease in heat transfer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Paul Richard Heinrich Blasius derived an exact solution to the above laminar boundary layer equations.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The thickness of the boundary layer $\delta$ is a function of the Reynolds number for laminar flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Note that in many cases, the no-slip boundary condition holds that $v_{S}$ , the fluid velocity at the surface of the plate equals the velocity of the plate at all locations.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] If the plate is not moving, then $v_{S}=0$ .
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] A much more complicated derivation is required if fluid slip is allowed.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In fact, the Blasius solution for laminar velocity profile in the boundary layer above a semi-infinite plate can be easily extended to describe Thermal and Concentration boundary layers for heat and mass transfer respectively.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For the momentum balance, kinematic viscosity $\nu$ can be considered to be the *momentum diffusivity*.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In the energy balance this is replaced by thermal diffusivity $\alpha ={k/\rho C_{P}}$ , and by mass diffusivity $D_{AB}$ in the mass balance.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] In thermal diffusivity of a substance, k is its thermal conductivity, $\rho$ is its density and $C_{P}$ is its heat capacity.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Subscript AB denotes diffusivity of species A diffusing into species B.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Under the assumption that $\alpha =D_{AB}=\nu$ , these equations become equivalent to the momentum balance.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Thus, for Prandtl number $Pr=\nu /\alpha =1$ and Schmidt number $Sc=\nu /D_{AB}=1$ the Blasius solution applies directly.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Accordingly, this derivation uses a related form of the boundary conditions, replacing v with T or $c_{A}$ (absolute temperature or concentration of species A).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The subscript S denotes a surface condition.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Using the streamline function Blasius obtained the following solution for the shear stress at the surface of the plate.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] where $\delta _{T},\delta _{c}$ are the regions of flow where T and $c_{A}$ are less than 99% of their far field values.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Because the Prandtl number of a particular fluid is not often unity, German engineer E.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Polhausen who worked with Ludwig Prandtl attempted to empirically extend these equations to apply for $Pr\neq 1$ .
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] His results can be applied to $Sc$ as well.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] From this solution, it is possible to characterize the convective heat/mass transfer constants based on the region of boundary layer flow.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Fourier's law of conduction and Newton's Law of Cooling are combined with the flux term derived above and the boundary layer thickness.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This gives the local convective constant $h_{x}$ at one point on the semi-infinite plane.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] These solutions apply for laminar flow with a Prandtl/Schmidt number greater than 0.6.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Many of the principles that apply to aircraft also apply to ships, submarines, and offshore platforms, with water as the primary fluid of concern rather than air.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] As water is not an ideal fluid, ships moving in water experience resistance.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] While the front of the ship faces normal pressure forces due to the fluid surrounding it, the aft portion sees a lower acting component of pressure due to the boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This leads to higher resistance due to pressure known as 'viscous pressure drag' or 'form drag'.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] For ships, unlike aircraft, one deals with incompressible flows, where change in water density is negligible (a pressure rise close to 1000kPa leads to a change of only 2–3 kg/m3).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This field of fluid dynamics is called hydrodynamics.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] A ship engineer designs for hydrodynamics first, and for strength only later.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] The boundary layer development, breakdown, and separation become critical because the high viscosity of water produces high shear stresses.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] This effect was exploited in the Tesla turbine, patented by Nikola Tesla in 1913.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It is referred to as a bladeless turbine because it uses the boundary layer effect and not a fluid impinging upon the blades as in a conventional turbine.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Boundary layer turbines are also known as cohesion-type turbine, bladeless turbine, and Prandtl layer turbine (after Ludwig Prandtl).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] By using the transient and viscous force equations for a cylindrical flow you can predict the transient boundary layer thickness by finding the Womersley Number ( $N_{w}$ ).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] where $N_{w}$ = Womersley Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $w=$ frequency of oscillations; $\delta _{1}$ = length of transient boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] By using the convective and viscous force equations at the boundary layer for a cylindrical flow you can predict the convective flow conditions at the boundary layer by finding the dimensionless Reynolds Number ( $Re$ ).
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] where $Re$ = Reynolds Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $\delta _{2}$ = length of convective boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Boundary layer ingestion promises an increase in aircraft fuel efficiency with an aft-mounted propulsor ingesting the slow fuselage boundary layer and re-energising the wake to reduce drag and improve propulsive efficiency.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] To operate in distorted airflow, the fan is heavier and its efficiency is reduced, and its integration is challenging.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It is used in concepts like the Aurora D8 or the French research agency Onera's Nova, saving 5% in cruise by ingesting 40% of the fuselage boundary layer.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Airbus presented the Nautilius concept at the ICAS congress in September 2018: to ingest all the fuselage boundary layer, while minimizing the azimuthal flow distortion, the fuselage splits into two spindles with 13-18:1 bypass ratio fans.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] Propulsive efficiencies are up to 90% like counter-rotating open rotors with smaller, lighter, less complex and noisy engines.
[src:cool-flame/boundary-layer] It could lower fuel burn by over 10% compared to a usual underwing 15:1 bypass ratio engine.
[src:cool-flame/butane] The name butane comes from the root but- (from butyric acid, named after the Greek word for butter) and the suffix -ane (for organic compounds).
[src:cool-flame/butane] The first synthesis of butane was accidentally achieved by British chemist Edward Frankland in 1849 from ethyl iodide and zinc, but he had not realized that the ethyl radical had dimerized, and thus misidentified the substance.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane was discovered in crude petroleum in 1864 by Edmund Ronalds, who was the first to describe its properties, which he named "hydride of butyl", based on the naming for the then-known butyric acid, which had been named and described by the French chemist Michel Eugène Chevreul 40 years earlier.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Other names arose in the 1860s: "butyl hydride", "hydride of tetryl" and "tetryl hydride", "diethyl" or "ethyl ethylide" and others.
[src:cool-flame/butane] August Wilhelm von Hofmann, in his 1866 systemic nomenclature, proposed the name "quartane", and the modern name was introduced to English from German around 1874.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane did not have much practical use until the 1910s, when W.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Snelling identified butane and propane as components in gasoline.
[src:cool-flame/butane] He found that if they were cooled, they could be stored in a volume-reduced liquified state in pressurized containers.
[src:cool-flame/butane] In 1911, Snelling's liquified petroleum gas was publicly available, and his process for producing the mixture was patented in 1913.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane is one of the most produced industrial chemicals in the 21st century, with around 80 to 90 billion lbs (40 million US tons, 36 million metric tons) produced by the United States every year.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Rotation about the central C−C bond produces four different conformations (*trans*, *gauche*, *cis* and anticlinal) for *n*-butane.
[src:cool-flame/butane] When oxygen is plentiful, butane undergoes complete combustion to form carbon dioxide and water vapor; when oxygen is limited, due to incomplete combustion, carbon (soot) or carbon monoxide may be formed instead of carbon dioxide.
[src:cool-flame/butane] The maximum adiabatic flame temperature of butane with air is 2,243 K (1,970 °C; 3,578 °F).
[src:cool-flame/butane] Normal butane can be used for gasoline blending, as a fuel gas, fragrance extraction solvent, either alone or in a mixture with propane, and as a feedstock for the manufacture of ethylene and butadiene, a key ingredient of synthetic rubber.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Isobutane is primarily used by refineries to enhance (increase) the octane number of motor gasoline.
[src:cool-flame/butane] For gasoline blending, *n*-butane is the main component used to manipulate the Reid vapor pressure (RVP).
[src:cool-flame/butane] Since winter fuel require much higher vapor pressure for engines to start, refineries raise the RVP by blending more butane into the fuel.
[src:cool-flame/butane] *n*-Butane has a relatively high research octane number (RON) and motor octane number (MON), which are 93 and 92 respectively.
[src:cool-flame/butane] When blended with propane and other hydrocarbons, the mixture may be referred to commercially as liquefied petroleum gas (LPG).
[src:cool-flame/butane] It is used as a petrol component, as a feedstock for the production of base petrochemicals in steam cracking, as fuel for cigarette lighters and as a propellant in aerosol sprays such as deodorants.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Pure forms of butane, especially isobutane, are used as refrigerants and have largely replaced the ozone-layer-depleting halomethanes in refrigerators, freezers, and air conditioning systems.
[src:cool-flame/butane] The operating pressure for butane is lower than operating pressures for halomethanes such as Freon-12 (R-12).
[src:cool-flame/butane] Hence, R-12 systems, such as those in automotive air conditioning systems, when converted to pure butane, will function poorly.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Instead, a mixture of isobutane and propane is used to give cooling system performance comparable to R-12.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane is also used as lighter fuel for common lighters or butane torches, and is sold bottled as a fuel for cooking, barbecues and camping stoves.
[src:cool-flame/butane] In the 20th century, the Braun company of Germany made a cordless hair styling device product that used butane as its heat source to produce steam.
[src:cool-flame/butane] As fuel, butane is often mixed with small amounts of mercaptans to give the unburned gas an offensive smell easily detected by the human nose.
[src:cool-flame/butane] In this way, butane leaks can easily be identified.
[src:cool-flame/butane] While hydrogen sulfide and mercaptans are toxic, they are present in levels so low that suffocation and fire hazard by the butane becomes a concern far before toxicity.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Most commercially available butane also contains some contaminant oil, which can be removed by filtration.
[src:cool-flame/butane] If not removed, it will otherwise leave a deposit at the point of ignition and may eventually block the uniform flow of gas.
[src:cool-flame/butane] The butane used as a solvent for fragrance extraction does not contain these contaminants.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane gas can cause gas explosions in poorly ventilated areas if leaks go unnoticed and are ignited by spark or flame.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Purified butane is used as a solvent in the industrial extraction of cannabis oils.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Inhalation of butane can cause euphoria, drowsiness, unconsciousness, asphyxia, cardiac arrhythmia, fluctuations in blood pressure and temporary memory loss, when abused directly from a highly pressurized container, and can result in death from asphyxiation and ventricular fibrillation.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane enters the blood supply, and within seconds, leads to intoxication.
[src:cool-flame/butane] Butane is the most commonly abused volatile substance in the UK, and was the cause of 52% of solvent related deaths in 2000.
[src:cool-flame/butane] By spraying butane directly into the throat, the jet of fluid can cool rapidly to −20 °C (−4 °F) by expansion, causing prolonged laryngospasm.
[src:cool-flame/butane] "Sudden sniffer's death" syndrome, first described by Bass in 1970, is the most common single cause of solvent related deaths, resulting in 55% of known fatal cases.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone may be produced by oxidation of 2-butanol.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] This is used to produce approximately 700 million kilograms yearly.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Other syntheses that have been examined but not implemented include Wacker oxidation of 2-butene and oxidation of isobutylbenzene, which is analogous to the industrial production of acetone.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] The cumene process can be modified to produce phenol and a mixture of acetone and butanone instead of only phenol and acetone in the original.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Both liquid-phase oxidation of heavy naphtha and the Fischer–Tropsch reaction produce mixed oxygenate streams, from which 2-butanone is extracted by fractionation.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone is an effective and common solvent and is used in processes involving gums, resins, cellulose acetate and nitrocellulose coatings and in vinyl films.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] For this reason it finds use in the manufacture of plastics, textiles, in the production of paraffin wax, and in household products such as lacquer, varnishes, paint remover, a denaturing agent for denatured alcohol, glues, and as a cleaning agent.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It is a prime component of plumbers' priming fluid, used to clean PVC materials.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It has similar solvent properties to acetone but boils at a higher temperature and has a significantly slower evaporation rate.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Unlike acetone, it forms an azeotrope with water, making it useful for azeotropic distillation of moisture in certain applications.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone is also used in dry erase markers as the solvent of the erasable dye.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] The hydroxylamine derivative of butanone is methylethyl ketone oxime (MEKO), which also find use in paints and varnishes as an anti-skinning agent.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] As butanone dissolves polystyrene and many other plastics, it is sold as "model cement" for use in connecting parts of scale model kits.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Though often considered an adhesive, it is functioning as a welding agent in this context.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone is the precursor to methyl ethyl ketone peroxide, which is a catalyst for some polymerization reactions such as crosslinking of unsaturated polyester resins.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] In the peroxide process on producing hydrazine, the starting chemical ammonia is bonded to butanone, oxidized by hydrogen peroxide, bonded to another ammonia molecule.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] In the final step of the process, hydrolysis produces the desired product, hydrazine, and regenerates the butanone.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone can react with most oxidizing materials and can produce fires.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It is moderately explosive, requiring only a small flame or spark to cause a vigorous reaction.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] The vapor is heavier than air, so it can accumulate at low points.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It is explosive at concentrations between 1.4 and 11.4%.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Concentrations in the air high enough to be flammable are intolerable to humans due to the irritating nature of the vapor.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone fires should be extinguished with carbon dioxide, dry agents, or alcohol-resistant foam.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] The ignition of butanone vapor was the proximate cause of the 2007 Xcel Energy Cabin Creek fire, resulting in the deaths of five workers in a hydroelectric penstock.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board specifically noted the danger posed by butanone in confined spaces, and suggested 1,1,1-trichloroethane or limonene as safer alternatives.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone is a constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It is an irritant, causing irritation to the eyes and nose of humans.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Serious animal health effects have been seen only at very high levels.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] There are no long-term studies with animals breathing or drinking it, and no studies for carcinogenicity in animals breathing or drinking it.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] There is some evidence that butanone can potentiate the toxicity of other solvents, in contrast to the calculation of mixed solvent exposures by simply adding exposures.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] As of 2010, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) listed butanone as a toxic chemical.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] There are reports of neuropsychological effects.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It is rapidly absorbed through undamaged skin and lungs.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] It contributes to the formation of ground-level ozone, which is toxic in low concentrations.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Butanone is listed as a Table II precursor under the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] Emission of butanone was regulated in the US as a hazardous air pollutant, because it is a volatile organic compound contributing to the formation of tropospheric (ground-level) ozone.
[src:cool-flame/butanone] In 2005, the US Environmental Protection Agency removed butanone from the list of hazardous air pollutants (HAPs).
[src:cool-flame/butyl-acetate] The other three isomers (four, including stereoisomers) of butyl acetate are isobutyl acetate, *tert*-butyl acetate, and *sec*-butyl acetate (two enantiomers).
[src:cool-flame/butyl-acetate] Butyl acetate is mainly used as a solvent for coatings and inks.
[src:cool-flame/butyl-acetate] Apples, especially of the "Red Delicious" variety, are flavored in part by this chemical.
[src:cool-flame/butyl-acetate] The alarm pheromones emitted by the Koschevnikov gland of honey bees contain butyl acetate.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] A **cool flame** is a flame having a typical temperature of about 400 °C (752 °F).
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] In contrast to an ordinary hot flame, the reaction is not vigorous and releases little heat, light, or carbon dioxide.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Cool flames are difficult to observe and are uncommon in everyday life, but they are responsible for engine knock – the undesirable, erratic, and noisy combustion of low-octane fuels in internal combustion engines.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Cool flames were accidentally discovered in the 1810s by Sir Humphry Davy, who inserted a hot platinum wire into a mixture of air and diethyl ether vapor.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] "When the experiment on the slow combustion of ether is made in the dark, a pale phosphorescent light is perceived above the wire, which of course is most distinct when the wire ceases to be ignited.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Harry Julius Emeléus was the first to record their emission spectra, and in 1929 he coined the term "cold flame".
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Cool flames can occur in hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes, oils, acids, waxes, and even methane.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The lowest temperature of a cool flame is poorly defined and is conventionally set as a temperature at which the flame can be detected by eye in a dark room (cool flames are hardly visible in daylight).
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] This temperature slightly depends on the fuel to oxygen ratio and strongly depends on gas pressure – there is a threshold below which cool flame is not formed.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] A specific example is 50% n-butane–50% oxygen (by volume) which has a cool flame temperature (CFT) of about 300 °C (572 °F) at 165 mmHg (22.0 kPa).
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] One of the lowest CFTs (156 °C (313 °F)) was reported for a C2H5OC2H5 + O2 + N2 mixture at 300 mmHg (40 kPa).
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The CFT is significantly lower than the auto-ignition temperature (AIT) of conventional flame (see table).
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The spectra of cool flames consist of several bands and are dominated by the blue and violet ones – thus the flame usually appears pale blue.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] A cool flame does not start instantaneously after the threshold pressure and temperature are applied, but has an induction time.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The induction time shortens and the glow intensity increases with increasing pressure.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] With increasing temperature, the intensity may decrease because of the disappearance of peroxy radicals required for the above glow reactions.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Self-sustained, stable cool diffusion flames have been established by adding ozone into oxidizer stream.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Whereas in a hot flame molecules break down to small fragments and combine with oxygen producing carbon dioxide (i.e., burn), in a cool flame, the fragments are relatively large and easily recombine with each other.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Therefore, much less heat, light and carbon dioxide is released; the premixed combustion process is oscillatory and can sustain for a long time.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] A typical temperature increase upon ignition of a cool flame is a few tens of degrees Celsius whereas it is on the order of 1,000 °C (1,830 °F) for a hot flame.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Most experimental data can be explained by the model which considers cool flame just as a slow chemical reaction where the rate of heat generation is higher than the heat loss.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] This model also explains the oscillatory character of the cool premixed flame: the reaction accelerates as it produces more heat until the heat loss becomes appreciable and temporarily quenches the process.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Unlike a cool premixed flame, a cool diffusion flame (CDF) burns in the presence of an equivalence ratio gradient.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] CDFs were first observed in 2012 in droplet experiments aboard the International Space Station.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Since then CDFs have been observed in microgravity spherical flames burning droplets and gases and in normal gravity counterflow and stratified flames.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Cool flames may contribute to engine knock – the undesirable, erratic, and noisy combustion of low-octane fuels in internal combustion engines.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] In a normal spark-ignition engine, the hot premixed flame front travels smoothly in the combustion chamber from the spark plug, compressing the fuel/air mixture ahead.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] However, the concomitant increase in pressure and temperature may produce a cool flame in the last unburned fuel-air mixture (the so-called end gasses) and participate in the autoignition of the end gasses.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] This sudden, localized heat release generates a shock wave which travels through the combustion chamber, with its sudden pressure rise causing an audible knocking sound.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Worse, the shock wave disrupts the thermal boundary layer on the piston surface, causing overheating and eventual melting.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The output power decreases and, unless the throttle (or load) is cut off quickly, the engine can be damaged as described in a few minutes.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The sensitivity of a fuel to a cool-flame ignition strongly depends on the temperature, pressure and composition.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The cool flame initiation of the knock process is likely only in highly throttled operating conditions, since cool flames are observed at low pressures.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Under normal operating conditions, autoignition occurs without being triggered by a cool flame.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] Whereas the temperature and pressure of the combustion are largely determined by the engine, the composition can be controlled by various antiknock additives.
[src:cool-flame/cool-flame] The latter mainly aim at removing the radicals (such as CH2O* mentioned above) thereby suppressing the major source of the cool flame.
